%N A397614 Decimal expansion of the large face angle, in radians, of a canonical (dual-uniform) hexagonal trapezohedron.
%C A397614 The hexagonal trapezohedron is the dual polyhedron of the hexagonal antiprism.
%C A397614 Its faces are kites with one acute angle (A397613) and three obtuse angles (this constant).
%H A397614 Paolo Xausa, <a href="/A397614/b397614.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A397614 David I. McCooey, <a href="https://dmccooey.com/polyhedra/HexagonalTrapezohedron.html">Hexagonal Trapezohedron</a>.
%H A397614 Polytope Wiki, <a href="https://polytope.miraheze.org/wiki/Hexagonal_antitegum">Hexagonal antitegum</a>.
%H A397614 Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, <a href="https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Trapezohedron.html">Trapezohedron</a>.
%H A397614 Wikipedia, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hexagonal_trapezohedron">Hexagonal trapezohedron</a>.
%H A397614 <a href="/index/Tra#transcendental">Index entries for transcendental numbers</a>.
%F A397614 Equals arccos((1 - sqrt(3))/2) = arccos((1 - A002194)/2).
%F A397614 Equals arccos(c), where c = -0.366025... is the smallest root of 2*x^2 - 2*x - 1.
%e A397614 1.945530759503636694165075001092234036804174140211...
%t A397614 First[RealDigits[ArcCos[(1 - Sqrt[3])/2], 10, 100]]
